0.body: This is a set of guides mostly covering how to install and set up software you'll need for this class. If you know what you're doing and want to use an alternative program or follow a different process, then you can. However, make sure that: You are complying with the academic integrity policy in our syllabus. Software that incorporates AI might be a problem. You know how to use and troubleshoot your alternative without my help. If you need me to fix a problem for you, then I will first ask you to follow the guides I've provided and see if that fixes the issue. You're capable of completing any assignments or other tasks necessary for this class using your alternative. If not, then follow the guides and use the recommended software.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: You should have a Linux, macOS, or Windows laptop (Chromebooks are not suitable for this class). Aside from the operating system (Linux, Mac, or Windows), there are a few other things you'll need to know about your computer.
1.title: Computer Information

10.body: I recommend enabling the autosave feature in this plugin's preferences. Choose whatever settings you'd prefer, or go with the following suggestions if you don't know what to choose: Check "Enable save when losing focus" so Geany saves whenever you switch to a terminal to run your program. Check "Enable" and set interval to 300 to autosave every five minutes.
10.title: Save Actions

11.body: The default settings should be fine. You can find the file browser in the sidebar (make sure View -> Show Sidebar is checked) under the Files tab. This can be a convenient way to find and edit files.
11.title: File Browser

12.body: If you want to have multiple files open and visible at once, you can enable a split view with Tools -> Split Window -> Side by Side (or Top and Bottom). The second panel can show any of your open tabs.
12.title: Split Window

13.body: You can find your settings under Edit -> Preferences. On Mac and Windows Preferences may be under a different menu, such as File or Geany. For now, the only setting I recommend changing is the "Startup Path" in the General section. Set this to your csc110 folder (see File Organization so that the file browser starts in a more convenient location whenever you open Geany.
13.title: Settings

14.body: Organize your files however you want, but make sure you know where they are and how to find them. I'll cover a simple setup that should make it easy to keep track of your work for this class. Go to your home directory and create a csc110 folder. You can use the command mkdir csc110 on your terminal. You can choose another location, but make sure it's easy to find. If it's in your home directory, then you can always reach it with the command cd ~/csc110. In your csc110 folder, create folders called labs, assignments, and classwork. You can also do this with the mkdir command. Set Geany to start in your csc110 folder (see Software Configuration ).
14.title: File Organization

15.body: We'll cover how to use your terminal during class. These guides are longer and more detailed to serve as a reference in case you forget something. We use the terminal constantly in this class, so it's important that you understand the basics of terminal commands, paths, and how to navigate your file system.
15.title: Terminal Navigation

16.body: You interact with a terminal by typing a command and reading the command's output. This section will cover the structure of a command and some terms you'll need to know to understand these commands. There are differences between Windows and Unix-like systems, but most of these differences won't matter if you are using a bash emulator on Windows. For example, Windows uses a backslash to separate directory names in paths, but your bash emulator should allow you to use a forward slash as if you were on a Mac or Linux computer. My notes focus on Unix-like systems, but I will try to note differences between Git Bash and bash/zsh when they come up.
16.title: Commands

17.body: Some terms that will be used to explain terminal commands. Refer back to this list if you come across something you don't understand. Directory : another word for a folder on your hard drive. A directory can contain files and other directories. Your working directory is the directory in which your terminal (or another program) is currently running. Your terminal has direct access to files in its working directory. Your home directory is the where the terminal starts. This should be your user folder: /home/username on Linux, /Users/username on Mac, and C:\Users\username (displayed as /c/Users/username in a bash emulator) on Windows. Path : a path is the location of a file or directory. It consists of directory names separated by forward slashes (/). The path ends with the name of the file or directory it leads to. An absolute path tells you how to reach a file or directory from the root of a file system. An absolute path starts with a forward slash on Unix-like systems. For example, the absolute path to my Desktop can be written as /home/zach/Desktop or /home/zach/Desktop/. The forward slash at the end of the path is optional, and it can only be included when the path points to a directory (such as the Desktop folder). A relative path tells you how to get from one location (usually your working directory) to a specific file or directory. For example, if I were in the directory /home/zach and wanted to reach /home/zach/Desktop/notes.txt, then the relative path Desktop/notes.txt tells me how to reach that file from my current location. Your computer also has a list of paths that it checks whenever you ask it to run a program. This list is stored under the label "path" or "PATH", and we can just refer to it as "the path". When you install a new program, the installer will usually add its location to the path or create a shortcut in a directory that was already on the path. If a program is on the path, then you only have to type its name to run it. If a program is not on the path, then you have to type a path to that program to run it.
17.title: Terms

18.body: Commands on the terminal can refer to programs or built-in functions. Sometimes you'll only need to type the name of a command, and sometimes you'll need to include arguments after the name. An argument is an additional piece of information that changes the command's behavior. Here are three examples using the ls command: ls: lists contents of working directory; no arguments ls Desktop: lists contents of the Desktop directory; Desktop is an argument ls -a Desktop: lists contents of the Desktop directory, including hidden files; -a and Desktop are arguments The third command includes a special type of argument called a flag . A flag normally starts with one or two dashes, and it enables a setting in the command. The -a flag tells ls to include hidden files in its output.
18.title: Command Structure

19.body: Spaces separate each part of a command (the name and arguments). This can cause problems if you use spaces in your filenames. For example, if you have a folder named My Folder, then the command ls My Folder will not list the contents of My Folder. It will instead try to list the contents of two directories: My and Folder. We can fix this by quoting the path (ls 'My Folder') or escaping the spaces (ls My\ Folder), but this is easy to forget and takes longer to type. If you avoid using spaces in filenames, then you don't have to worry about this.
19.title: Spaces

2.body: When downloading software, you may need to know what kind of CPU your computer has (the CPU's "architecture") to choose the correct version of that software. You most likely have an x86_64 (abbreviated x64) CPU or an aarch64 (also called arm64) CPU. To check: Linux: Open your terminal and run uname -m. Mac: Check About This Mac . Older Macs have x86_64 CPU's, and newer Mac's have aarch64 CPUs. Windows: Open "About your PC" in system settings and check "System type". You most likely have an x86_64 CPU if you're using Windows.
2.title: Architecture

20.body: Your terminal saves a history of every command you enter. You can go back through this history with the up and down arrow keys, which lets you repeat a command without retyping it. The tab key will attempt to complete the path or command name you are currently typing. This saves a lot of typing AND helps you avoid mistakes. If you haven't typed enough to narrow it down to one possibility, then you can hit tab again to see a list of every remaining option.
20.breadcrumbs: Terminal » Commands » Command History and Tab Completion
20.title: Command History and Tab Completion

21.body:
If I want to show you what it looks like when you run a terminal command, then I will include both the command and its output. It might look something like this: $ ls -a ~/Desktop
. .. todo.txt lesson_plan.md Terminals display a prompt when you are allowed to type a command. This prompt can include your username and working directory, and it usually ends in a dollar sign, percent sign, or other special character. When you type a command, it will appear after that special character. For example, the prompt on my work desktop terminal looks like this before I type a command: zach@zach-work-desktop:~$ If I type the command ls -a ~/Desktop, then it will appear after the prompt: zach@zach-work-desktop:~$ ls -a ~/Desktop We usually use a lone dollar sign at the start of a line to abbreviate this prompt, but it is not part of the command. For example, if you wanted to imitate the example below, then you would only type ls -a ~/Desktop on your terminal and press the enter key. $ ls -a ~/Desktop
. .. todo.txt lesson_plan.md Here's a longer example involving five terminal commands, two of which produce output: $ cd Desktop/csc110
bash: cd: csc110: No such file or directory
$ cd Desktop
$ mkdir csc110
$ ls
csc110
$ cd csc110 In the above example, I ran the commands cd Desktop/csc110, cd Desktop, mkdir csc110, ls, and cd csc110. The messages bash: cd: csc110: No such file or directory and csc110 were the output of two of those commands.
21.title: Examples

22.body: Before you can use the terminal to run your programs, you need to know how to navigate your filesystem and find those programs. This is essential for doing anything in the terminal. The following three commands will help: pwd (print working directory): tells you where you are cd (change directory): moves the terminal to a new folder ls (list): lists files and folders in your current location
22.title: Navigation

23.body: Run pwd to print the absolute path of your working directory. You won't need to use this command often, but it's useful if you aren't sure exactly where you are.
23.title: pwd

24.body: Running cd with no arguments will take you to your home directory. Running cd followed by a directory's path will take you to that directory. You can use a relative or absolute path. For example: If I'm in the directory /home/zach/, which contains the directory Documents, then I can move into Documents with cd Documents or cd /home/zach/Documents/. If I'm in /home/, then I can move into Documents with cd zach/Documents or cd /home/zach/Documents/, but not cd Documents. Finally, there are a few special names that act as shortcuts for commonly-used directories: ~ Refers to your home directory. In the above example, I could reach my Documents folder from any location with cd ~/Documents. . Refers to the working directory. You won't need to use this one right now, but you may see it in some paths or after running the ls -a command. .. Refers to the working directory's parent directory. This is useful if you want to go back to a directory that appears earlier in your path. For example, if your working directory is /home/zach/Documents/csc110/homework/, then .. refers to /home/zach/Documents/csc110/. You can use .. multiple times to go back further. In the previous example, ../.. would refer to /home/zach/Documents/, and cd ../.. would move me to that directory.
24.title: cd

25.body: Running ls with no arguments will list the contents of your working directory. Running ls followed by a path will list the contents of that directory (if the path points to a directory) or the name of that file (if the path points to a file). This command is helpful if you're looking for a file or want to see what's in your current location. The -a flag mentioned earlier will show hidden files, and the -l flag will show more details about the files.
25.title: ls

26.body: In this class, most (possibly all) of our programs will be written as Compact Source Files . It's not necessary to understand what exactly this means right now, but you can read the relevant JDK Enhancement Proposal if you want the details. For now, I'll summarize the main points: Java normally requires a lot of boilerplate to write even the simplest program. That boilerplate code involves Java features that a new programmer won't be equipped to understand. Basic input and output (I/O) operations, which most of our programs will need, also require features that are difficult for new programmers to understand. A compact source file is a more concise way of writing a Java program. It removes most of the boilerplate from small programs and provides easier access to I/O functions. This lets us focus on the actual program we're trying to write and introduce new concepts when we're ready for them. This guide will cover how to convert standard Java programs into compact Java programs. This may be useful if: You have prior Java experience and want a quick guide for converting the way you normally code to the way we code in this class. You're looking at an example that doesn't use the new compact source features. These features are new, so most textbooks and online examples don't use them.

3.body: Your home directory is where your terminal should start and where you'll find many familiar folders like Documents and Desktop. You can run echo $HOME on your bash or zsh terminal to print the path of your home directory. Depending on your operating system, this will normally be: Linux: /home/username Mac: /Users/username Windows: /c/Users/username Windows formats paths differently from Linux and Mac, so you may also see this displayed as C:\Users\username outside of your Git Bash terminal. Note: "username" is a placeholder for your actual username. My username is "zach" and I have a Linux computer, so my home directory is /home/zach.
3.title: Home Directory

30.title: 4. Input

4.body: This class requires you to have a terminal, text editor, and the Java 25 JDK (or Java 24 until Java 25 is officially released).
4.title: Software Installation

5.body: If you're on Windows, install Git for Windows , which includes Git Bash. The terminal programs that come with Windows are not compatible with some of the terminal commands you'll see in class. You'll need a terminal that runs bash or a similar shell in order to follow along with my examples. If you're on Linux or Mac, then your default terminal running bash or zsh should be fine.
5.title: Terminal

6.body: The recommended text editor for this class is Geany . You can download an installer from the releases page for Mac or Windows (make sure you get the arm64 installer if your Mac has an aarch64 CPU), and you can use your package manager to install it on Linux.
6.title: Geany

7.body: We'll be using some new features that were previewed in Java 24 and will be finalized in Java 25. You should install Java 25 when it becomes available on September 16th, but until then you can use Java 24 and enable preview features when running your programs. We'll cover enabling preview features when we write our first program. The Eclipse Foundation provides free builds of the JDK (Java Development Kit), which you can download from their releases page . Click "All Versions", then select your operating system, architecture, and version 25 (or 24 if 25 is not yet available). Choose the .MSI (Windows) or .PKG (Mac) installers. The .ZIP and .TAR.GZ archives require manual installation. On Linux, you should check your package manager to see whether it has version 24 or 25 of Java. If not, then you can manually install the .TAR.GZ download. Please see me during office hours if you need help with this. After you install java, you can confirm that it was installed correctly by restarting your terminal and running the command java -version. This should show the version number of your Java installation (24 or 25).
7.title: Java
